Let $P$ be a point within the triangle $ABC$. When points $A$, $B$, and $C$ are folded onto $P$, we get three creases i.e. lines $\overline{PA}, \overline{PB}$, and $\overline{PC}$. For $P$ to not be a fold point, these three creases must intersect at a point other than $P$. That is, they must coincide with the circumcircle of $ABC$. Therefore, $P$ must lie outside the circumcircle and on neither of the sides of the three lines. Consequently, $P$ must lie in the region between two of the lines that does not contain the interior of the third line. Let $O$ be the circumcenter and $R$ be the circumradius of $\triangle ABC$. As $\angle B=90^\circ$, $\overline{AC}$ is the diameter of the circumcircle. Moreover, since $O$ is also the midpoint of $\overline{AC}$, then $AO=CO=R=36$. The lines $\overline{PA}, \overline{PB}$, and $\overline{PC}$ do not intersect if and only if $P$ lies outside the circumcircle and on the extensions of two of the lines tangent to the circumcircle at $A$ and $C$. By Thales' theorem, the two lines tangent at $A$ is 
\[ \angle AFB = 90^\circ \]
Thus, the area of region $G$ where $P$ lies is$\qquad$ \begin{align*}
 \begin{split}
 \text{Area of triangle } AOC - \frac{\text{Area of sector $AOC$}}{2} &= (\frac{1}{2})(R^2) - \frac{\pi(R)^2}{2} \\
&= \frac{1}{2}(36^2) - \frac{\pi(36)^2}{2} \\
&= 648 - 324\pi \\
&= \boxed{648-324\pi}
 \end{split}
 \quad \boxed{\begin{aligned}
\text{The area of the set of all fold points is }\;& 648-324\pi.\\
\text{Thus, }q+r+s=\boxed{972}. \end{aligned}} 
 \end{align*} </think> <answer>648-324\pi\\972</answer>

